<article>
	<h2>Our logo</h2>
	<img src="/images/pacific-logo-vertical.png" />
	<div>
		<p>The Pacific Regional Council on Early Childhood Development (PRC4ECD) has chosen baby sea turtle as its symbol, as it represents both childhood and the Pacific community as a whole. Turtles are considered sacred in many Pacific cultures, symbolizing longevity, wellness, and protection &mdash; all of which are intrinsic to the concept of early childhood development. A baby turtle, specifically, represents strength, resilience, and even hope: this tiny, vulnerable creature &mdash; swimming in a huge expanse of ocean &mdash; will grow into a majestic giant that may live for hundreds of years and swim thousands of miles.</p>
		<p>Turtles range widely across the Pacific. They are not associated with any single nation, and thus act as an inclusive symbol for the Blue Continent’s whole community. They are, finally, a symbol of the community’s complexity and potential: they live in the water, in the vast depths, always moving, swimming from one place to another like connecting threads in the vast and diverse Pacific.</p>
	</div>
